We investigated the sensitivity of N,S-CDs to Arg with different response times and different buffer solutions. As shown in Fig. S9, except for the first minute, the fluorescence quenching intensity of N,S-CDs changed little, indicating that the reaction time kept the fluorescence intensity basically stable within 2–10 min. Besides, the type of buffer solution had no significant effect on the determination of Arg (Fig. S10). Therefore, we chose PBS buffer solution with similar composition to body fluid. Fig. 4
                        A displayed that with the introduction of Arg, the PL intensity of N,S-CDs dropped. The relationship between (F0–F)/F0 and the concentration of Arg was fitted by the ExpDec equation, and he fitting constant was 0.9956 (Fig. 4B). A good linear relationship, y = 0.0069x+0.0174 R2 = 0.9920), was fitted between (F0–F)/F0 and Arg content within the range 2.5–62.5 μM (Fig. 4C). The detection limit (LOD) of Arg is as per Formula 3σ/Slope calculation, as low as 0.68 μM. Compared with other CD-based Arg sensors, N,S-CDs have the longest emission wavelength (Table 1
                        ). To further inspect the specificity of Arg, the effects of 17 kinds of common amino acids on the luminescence of N,S-CDs were assessed. The result demonstrated that only Arg could quench the fluorescence of N,S-CDs (Fig. 4D).

The application of N,S-CDs as imaging reagents in vivo was further explored. As an excellent animal model, zebrafish is widely used for in vivo imaging. As shown in Fig. 7
                        , the fluorescence in zebrafish gradually disappeared with the increase of pH. In addition, after the introduction of Arg, the fluorescence in zebrafish gradually decreased (Fig. 8
                        ). All the results demonstrated that N,S-CDs are a promising nanomaterial for imaging.

Due to the excellent photostability of N,S-CDs, we developed their application as photovoltaic materials. On the one hand, N,S-CDs/starch fluorescent powder was prepared, which emits bright orange fluorescence under UV light irradiation (Fig. 9
                        ). On the other hand, N,S-CDs/PVA fluorescent flexible films were prepared. As the concentration of N,S-CDs increased, the orange fluorescence of the films gradually enhanced (Fig. 10
                        ).
